"Dodd R.S., Afzal Rafii Z.","Evolutionary genetics of mangroves: Continental drift to recent climate change",2002,"Trees - Structure and Function","16","2-3",,"80","86",,,10.1007/s00468-001-0142-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036521003&partnerID=40&md5=078e71f39ce161f8b4946de336a670db","Department of Environmental Science Policy and Management, University of California Berkeley, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; IME, PUMR 6610, Université d'Aix-Marseille III, 13397 Marseille Cedex 13, France","Dodd, R.S., Department of Environmental Science Policy and Management, University of California Berkeley, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Afzal Rafii, Z., IME, PUMR 6610, Université d'Aix-Marseille III, 13397 Marseille Cedex 13, France","Recent advances in our knowledge of the genetic architecture of mangrove species are reviewed and the consequences of this genetic architecture for species response to environmental change are inferred. The origins of mangrove taxa have been discussed many times, particularly in the context of centers of origin and continental drift. While global patterns of mangrove species diversity have been interpreted in the context of tectonic events and opening and closing of seawater passages, species evolution on a finer scale depends on more recent processes of population extinction and advances in response to spatio-temporal climatic and environmental flux. Understanding the likely effects of global climate change on mangrove distributions requires a focus on these more recent intraspecific evolutionary processes. Many mangrove taxa have wide geographic ranges that have been attributed to efficient propagule dispersal. Such gene flow should provide a genetic cohesiveness among populations. However, as with many wide-ranging marine organisms, we are finding important population genetic structure in widespread mangrove species, suggesting that gene flow is less effective than previously thought. Are these widespread taxa more recent and undergoing speciation? Spatial patterns in genetically adaptive traits indicate that some populations may survive more successfully under changing environmental conditions. However, is the present-day genetic architecture best poised to respond to predictions of climate change? These questions are addressed in the light of our increasing knowledge of genetic diversity in mangrove species.","AFLP; Avicennia germinans; Biogeography; Cuticular waxes; Genetic variation","Climate change; Environmental impact; Genetic algorithms; Marine applications; Population statistics; Genetic diversity; Plants (botany); Avicennia; Avicennia germinans; Embryophyta; Rhizophoraceae",,,,,,"Rafii, Z.A., Dodd, R.S., Fauvel, M.-T., A case of natural selection in Atlantic-East Pacific Rhizophora (1999) Hydrobiologia, 413, pp. 1-9; Abeysinghe, P.D., Triest, L., De Greef, B., Koedam, N., Hettiarachi, S., Genetic differentiation between Bruguiera gymnorhiza and B. sexangula in Sri Lanka (1999) Hydrobiologia, 413, pp. 11-16; Balakrishna, P., Evaluation of intra-specific variability in Avicennia marina Forsk. using RAPD markers (1995) Curr Sci, 69, pp. 926-929; Ballment, E.R., Smith, T.J., Stoddart, J.A., Sibling species in the mangrove genus Ceriops (Rhizophoraceae) detected using biochemical genetics (1988) Aust Syst Bot, 1, pp. 391-397; Berner, R.A., Paleozoic atmospheric CO2: Importance of solar radiation and plant evolution (1993) Science, 261, pp. 68-70; Bousquet-Mélou, A., (1996) Biosystématique de Palétuviers du Genre Avicennia: Rechereche de Nouveaux Marqueurs Taxonomiques, , PhD thesis, Université Paul Sabatier, Toulouse, France; Bunt, J.S., Williams, W.T., Duke, N.C., Mangrove distributions in northeast Australia (1982) J Biogeogr, 9, pp. 111-120; Burke, L.A., Kura, Y., Kassem, K., Revenga, C., Spalding, M., McAllister, D., (2001) Pilot Analysis of Global Ecosystems: Coastal Ecosystems, , World Resources Institute, Washington, DC; Chandler, M.E.J., Note on the occurrence 